I designed this using Designspark Mechanical and I have included the rsdoc file for editing it. title: Ninja Lock - Indoor Child Door Lock
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
If you have kids, chances are they are ninja's just like mine. These little ninja's will get into anything and everything (including taking a sharpie to your white kitchen cabinets). I designed this device that slips over the door (preferably near the top) and locks the door within the door frame so that we can stop our little ninjas in their tracks. It also has a built in mechanism to prevent smashed fingers. I've tested this with my 3 and 2 year old. It works great! Let me know what you guys/gals think in the comments and/or if you would like to see modifications. I plan to improve and come out with more child ninja safety in the future. *Update: Added the .f3d file from Autodesk Fusion 360. Update (10/23/15) - After a good solid month of use, I had one of these snap right in bend of the arm near the pet that latches onto the door. I'm working on a fix for for this to make it stronger.
Also, I have some changes that should help with the triangle part scratching the door frame. My print bed is jacked up so as soon as I get some new glass, I can test it. Feel free to comment or PM me if you have any ideas on improvement. https://youtu.be/iA1tRmMiJ1M

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.3

Infill:

40%

Notes: I printed in ABS. I haven't done much with PLA so I do not know about PLA prints. You'll want to rotate the object 90 degrees on the X axis. Prints without supports. As you can see in the video, I might suggest printing in clear or white as some of the black rubbed off onto the door jam..

description.text: If you're having problems with the edges of your prints peeling, try using Helper Disks! These Helper Disks were designed by Thingiverse user ctheroux: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:51066 First, open a model. Then add a Helper Disk from this menu and use the Move tool to move the Helper Disk to one corner of your object, so the disk just slightly overlaps with the corner of the object on the plate. Use Copy and Paste to create more helper disks, and add one to each corner of your model. Then go ahead and print! The Helper Disks will increase the surface area of your model and help it stick to the platform without peeling. When your print finishes, you can remove the Helper Disks by cutting or peeling them off. Still having trouble getting your prints to stick? Do you own a camera and one or more tripods? Have you ever been in a situation where you aren't able to securely attach the tripod plate to the camera, or even to remove the plate, all because you didn't have a coin on you at that moment? If so, then this coin holder solves that problem by letting you store a coin with your tripod so that it is always available. 
There is a hole in the holder where you can install a small magnet, especially useful to hold coins that are magnetic (not that common, but you can also just use a large washer in place of the coin if needed). This holder is sized to fit the tripod and coin I had on hand. I found that a Chinese Yuan I had was magnetic (and no, I'm not from China). You may need to edit to fit your tripod leg and coin size.

description.text: This is a hood and filter holder for the DYS 3-axis SMART GoPro gimbal. It was designed specifically for the Formatt Hitech GoPro Filters: http://www.bhphotovideo.com/c/product/1032721-REG/hitech_htgpnd0_6kit5_0_6_neutral_density_filter.html Each filter is about 2$, so I use them to both protect the lens and reduce the shutter speed of the GoPro, for smoother video. When the filter gets scratched or dull, I just throw it away and put a new one. The part is designed for easy filter swap in the field, without any tools. Total weight with screws and filter is about 10g. The purpose of the hood or cap is to reduce glare from the sun, but mostly it's there to prevent propeller shadow strobing. My GoPro was modified with a 4.35mm 10MP Lens with a 72 degree field of view, so I don't know if the hood won't be visible when using the stock lens. Therefore, I included a version without the hood. The part is attached to the gimbal bracket using two (x2) 4mm M2 screws. You need the bracket or it won't fit. Look at the pictures to figure out how to assemble it.

title: Scary Monsters and Nice Sprites by Skrillex

description.text: Make your 3D printer play music. Using the sounds a printer motor makes naturally its possible to convert a song into G-code that tells the printer to move along its axes in a way that creates a song. The provided G-code is for the Scary Monsters and Nice Sprites by Skrillex.

• Under the slicer configuration settings go to printer settings.
  • Under printer settings, select custom G-code.
  • Here you will insert the G-code on the next line after G28.
  • Type G28 after the last line in the G-code if you want your printer to re-home after the song.
  • Save, and name the printer setting Scary Monsters and Nice Sprites.
  • Now when you load an object to print and are ready to slice it select Scary Monsters and Nice Sprites as your printer setting in the Slic3r menu.
  • Once you select start print the printer will home all axes and then begin playing while your extruder warms up! Before the song plays it will go to its starting position to verify the print bed dimensions. Once the song is done it will re-home all axes and then begin your print.
    • Note:
    The instructions demonstrate the use of this code using Repetier and Slic3r. I don't know how well it will work on other platforms. I've noticed when loading the .nc file if you copy and paste into your custom g-code sometimes the code is too long and will not paste all at once. It may take copy and pasting portions of code into the custom code a few parts at a time. Caution:
    This code was generated to the dimensions of a printrbot simple's print bed. Given that this is a small four by four inch print bed there shouldn't be any points in the code that is out of range for most printers ,however, I do advise that you use it at your on risk. I would also like to give credit to HomeConstructor for the software I used to convert MIDI to g-code. Here is a link:
    http://en.homeconstructor.de/converter-convert-music-in-g-code.html

description.text: Make your 3D printer play music. Using the sounds a printer motor makes naturally its possible to convert a song into G-code that tells the printer to move along its axes in a way that creates a song. The provided G-code is for the Gilligan's Island Theme.

• Under the slicer configuration settings go to printer settings.
  • Under printer settings, select custom G-code.
  • Here you will insert the G-code on the next line after G28.
  • Type G28 after the last line in the G-code if you want your printer to re-home after the song.
  • Save, and name the printer setting Gilligan's Island.
  • Now when you load an object to print and are ready to slice it select Gilligan's Island as your printer setting in the Slic3r menu.
  • Once you select start print the printer will home all axes and then begin playing while your extruder warms up! Before the song plays it will go to its starting position to verify the print bed dimensions. Once the song is done it will re-home all axes and then begin your print.
    Note:
    The instructions demonstrate the use of this code using Repetier and Slic3r. I don't know how well it will work on other platforms.
    • I've noticed when loading the .nc file if you copy and paste into your custom g-code sometimes the code is too long and will not paste all at once. It may take copy and pasting portions of code into the custom code a few parts at a time. Caution:
    This code was generated to the dimensions of a printrbot simple's print bed. Given that this is a small four by four inch print bed there shouldn't be any points in the code that is out of range for most printers ,however, I do advise that you use it at your on risk. I would also like to give credit to HomeConstructor for the software I used to convert MIDI to g-code. Here is a link:
    http://en.homeconstructor.de/converter-convert-music-in-g-code.html

    • Assembly The holes for the nuts are undersized, to put them in

description.text: Remember a relaxing day at the beach with this simple, colorful ocean scene lasercut from foamcore. This piece is one of several vignette designed around Inventor Studio's Lasercut Foamcore Scenes, a simple interlocking geometry system for foamcore. Like this scene, but want one with a palm tree next to the sand? Maybe what's missing is a dolphin playfully jumping across the boat's bow. Design additional elements yourself using the included interlocking base shape and make this scene your own. Teachers might consider using this interlocking system in makerspaces and other project-based classroom learning environments. Other designs released so far in this series can be found here, here, and here. Don't forget sunblock.

Lasercutting & Assembly Instructions An SVG file has been included for each color used in this design. Cutting the pieces on your laser should be very straightforward if you've cut foamcore before. Multi-pass cuts using reduced power are recommended, because this reduces the amount of foam shrinkage. Some layers in this design involve gluing different colored pieces onto the base part. Look carefully at the photo, paying attention to whether the additional pieces are glued in front or in back of the base piece. Inexpensive bailing wire and painters tape are used to attach hanging elements of the scene.

Designed Using Inkscape & Tinkercad Inventor Studios' Lasercut Foamcore Scenes are designed using Tinkercad and Inkscape. You can either edit the Inkscape SVG files found in this Thing directly or import them into Tinkercad to make modifications to this scene or create wholly new scenes for yourself, for classroom instruction, and to share with others.

description.text:
About a year ago at a party, a coworker heard about 3D printing for the first time and asked me if it would be able to print a replacement for the broken arm of his ping pong table (which holds up the net). I said of course it could do that, and then procrastinated for over a year getting around to designing and printing it for him.  
At first I was just going to print an L shape with the holes in the right place, but I eventually decided I might as well model it to closely match the original.

Print with the cylindrical arm on the bottom and the base sticking up in the air. When the print is done, break off the two round support pads (and the small rectangles connected to them).  
Screw an M3x25 screw into the bottom of the base until the head and a few mm of the bolt is all that's visible. Use whatever mounting screws your old ping pong arm used to mount it to the table, on the other side of the base (see pics for side-by-side comparison with the broken original).  
As I understand it the end of the net has a string that goes through the circular notch at the end of the half cylinder, then down the outside of the cylinder, then loops around the M3 bolt.

To avoid those awkward moments when you wish you had inserted a T-nut in your newly mounted delta (or any other open-build based machinery for that matter) to secure any accessory...
This one can be introduced into the slot from the top, no need to access from the side.

This inline 4 cylinder engine block is designed to use with my rotating assembly parts. I cut away part of the front of the block to allow for easy viewing of the internals in motion. The color picture is of the whole lower end minus the hand crank adapter, but this thing is just the block and stand. Get the rest of the parts here: Engine Crankshaft:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:102180 Piston and Rod with bolts, nuts, and pins included:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:100282 Hand crank for the crankshaft:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:103329 I have all the parts translated into position in the scad files but commented out to allow for playing with the fitment but it should all line up with minimal gaps to allow for freely moving parts right out of the box. If the tolerance is too tight, a nice acetone bath for the pistons and crank should grease things right up!

The block prints deck-first (vertical but upside down) and prints 102mm tall, but it's not very wide/long. I have an 8x8 bed and I don't even use the whole thing yet I still have no problem printing everything. The biggest print is the crank.
